# Deploying to Vercel

This is a static site plus one serverless function (`/api/contact.js`) that emails
enquiries from the contact form to **smithturnerconstruction@gmail.com**.
No build step and no npm dependencies — it deploys as-is.

## 1. Put the folder on Vercel
Either:
- **Drag & drop:** zip the `smith-and-turner` folder and drop it onto https://vercel.com/new, **or**
- **Git:** push the folder to a GitHub/GitLab repo, then "Import Project" in Vercel.

When importing, use **Framework Preset: Other**. Leave Build Command and Output
Directory blank (root is served as-is; `/api` is auto-detected as a function).

## 2. Turn on email delivery (one environment variable)
The form works immediately on deploy — but until this is set, it falls back to
opening a pre-filled email in the visitor's mail app instead of sending server-side.

To have submissions land in the inbox automatically:

1. Create a free account at **https://resend.com** using
   `smithturnerconstruction@gmail.com`.
2. Go to **API Keys → Create API Key**, copy the key (starts with `re_`).
3. In Vercel: **Project → Settings → Environment Variables**, add:
   - **Name:** `RESEND_API_KEY`   **Value:** *(the key you copied)*
4. **Redeploy** (Vercel → Deployments → ⋯ → Redeploy).

That's it. Enquiries will arrive at your Gmail, and hitting "reply" replies straight
to the person who submitted (their address is set as reply-to).

### Optional
- `CONTACT_TO` — send enquiries somewhere other than the default Gmail.
- `CONTACT_FROM` — a sender on your own **verified domain** (e.g.
  `Smith & Turner <hello@smithandturner.com.au>`). Until you verify a domain in
  Resend, leave this unset — it uses Resend's shared test sender, which can deliver
  to your own inbox without any domain setup.

